"We must know and be out of all doubt, that the Pope hath but a devilish Synagogue, and that all his Clergy is but filth & stench, all these varlets that have cast aside the Church of God, are but vermin. Although the Pope, who is Antichrist, be set in God's sanctuary, (as we have seen before [2 Thes. 2.4]) yet notwithstanding, he is not worthy to be taken and accounted for a minister of the Church, nor all his mates." John Calvin, Sermon on 1 Timothy, ch. 3. The 22 Sermon upon the second Chapter Sermons on Timothy and Titus

"And as for the Pope, I refuse him, as Christ's enemy and Antichrist, with all his false doctrine." The remains of Thomas Cranmer, Archbishop of Canterbury (ed. 1833)

"Whereof it followeth Rome to be the seat of antichrist, and the pope to be very antichrist himself. I could prove the same by many other scriptures, old writers, and strong reasons." Thomas Cranmer (1846). Miscellaneous Writings and Letters of Thomas Cranmer, p.63. The remains of Thomas Cranmer, Archbishop of Canterbury (ed. 1833)

Good morning beloved. My comment above was not intended to poke fun at Catholics, nor to offend them, though I'm sure it would do that. 

Many Christians including Luther and other reformers saw the Papacy as antichrist and as the Man of Sin the Apostle Paul warned about in 2 Thessalonians 2:3, 4. I'm inclined to think that way as well. Revelation warned that a false church would arise out of the Roman empire, and it would be a harlot compared to the true Bride of Christ, the Church. It would also be drunk with the blood of the saints. 

"Christianity" is so often blamed for evils like the Crusades and the Inquisition, but I ask: were those people following what Jesus taught in carrying out those actions? Jesus said, ‚ÄúIf you hold to my teaching, you are really my disciples" (John 8:31). I think the true Bride of Christ is falsely blamed for the actions of the harlot. While I do believe there can be true followers of Christ in the Roman Catholic Church, if you learn better that you should "have nothing to do with the fruitless works of darkness" (Ephesians 5:11), then you need to ‚ÄúCome out of her, my people, so that you will not share in her sins" (Revelation 18:4). 

This is not an endorsement of Orthodoxy (because I think they get some things wrong, too), but they were the original protestants.
